Absa, Impala, Massmart, Sentula Telkom: South African Stock Market Preview

-- B y   S t e p h e n   G u n n i o n
-- 
2011-06-28T22:00:01Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-28/absa-impala-massmart-telkom-south-african-equity-preview.html
The following stocks may rise or
fall in  South Africa  today. Symbols are in parentheses and
prices are from the last close.  The FTSE/JSE Africa All Share Index rose for a third day,
gaining 394.60, or 1.3 percent, to 31,291.65 at the 5 p.m. close
in Johannesburg.  Absa Group Ltd. (ASA)  : The chief executive officer of
South Africa’s largest retail bank,  Maria Ramos , speaks at the
Lafferty World Banking Summit in London. The stock rose 3.05
rand, or 2.3 percent, to 134.80 rand.  Famous Brands Ltd. (FBR)  : The country’s biggest fast-
food franchise owner holds its annual general meeting. Shares
were up 72 cents, or 1.7 percent, at 43.93 rand.  Impala Platinum Holdings Ltd. (IMP)  : David Brown, chief
executive officer of the world’s second-largest platinum
producer, discusses the company’s short- and long-term corporate
strategy at a Gordon Institute of Business Science Forum event.
The stock rose 2.56 rand, or 1.4 percent, to 181 rand.  Massmart Holdings Ltd. (MSM)  : The South African retailer
in which Wal-Mart Stores Inc. has bought a controlling stake,
updates the media on the potential benefits for South African
stakeholders. The Competition Tribunal is also scheduled to
release its reasons for approving the takeover by Wal-Mart
subject to conditions. The shares ended 4.29 rand, or 3.2
percent firmer, at 138.40 rand.  Sentula Mining Ltd. (SNU)  : The coal-mining company said
it had been advised that shareholders of Shanduka Group Ltd. had
not approved a planned exchange of shares and would not approve
the plan by the June 30 deadline. The stock gained 9 cents, or
3.4 percent, to 2.77 rand.  Telkom SA Ltd. (TKG)  : Africa’s largest fixed-line phone
operator, said it had reached an agreement through which an
affiliate of Helios Towers Nigeria Ltd. will acquire full
ownership and control of Multi-Links. Shares rose 25 cents, or
0.7 percent, to 35.45 rand.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Stephen Gunnion in Johannesburg at 
 sgunnion@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
